Function to convert coordinates¶

from astropy.coordinates import SkyCoord
import astropy.units as u

def convert_to_sexagesimal(ra_deg, dec_deg, format_hskymon=False):
    """Convert RA DEC from decimal degrees to sexagesimal hours and sexagesimal degrees
    Args:
        ra_deg (float): Right Ascension in decimal degrees.
        dec_deg (float): Declination in decimal degrees.
        format_hskymon (bool): If True, format for hskymon (no colons).
    Returns:
        tuple: RA in sexagesimal hours and DEC in sexagesimal degrees.
    """

    # Create a SkyCoord object with RA and DEC in decimal degrees
    coord = SkyCoord(ra_deg, dec_deg, unit=(u.deg, u.deg), frame='icrs')

    # Convert to sexagesimal format
    ra_sexagesimal = coord.ra.to_string(unit=u.hour, sep=':')
    dec_sexagesimal = coord.dec.to_string(unit=u.degree, sep=':')

    if format_hskymon:
        ra_sexagesimal = ra_sexagesimal.replace(":", "")
        dec_sexagesimal = dec_sexagesimal.replace(":", "")

    return ra_sexagesimal, dec_sexagesimal

CARMENES¶

Telluric-corrected high-SNR template spectra from:
Nagel et al. (2023) "The CARMENES search for exoplanets around M dwarfs. Telluric absorption corrected high S/N optical and near-infrared template spectra of 382 M dwarf stars"

Note that the spectra can be downloaded from the CARMENES GTO Data Archive: http://carmenes.cab.inta-csic.es/gto/jsp/tellurics_tac.jsp

colnames = ["Seq", "ID", "Name", "GJ", "RAh", "RAm", "RAs", "DE-", "DEd", "DEm", "DEs", "SpType", "Jmag", "VISobs", "VISsnr", "NIRobs", "NIRsnr",]
widths = [3, 12, 24, 7, 3, 3, 6, 2, 2, 3, 5, 5, 6, 4, 5, 4, 5]
df_carmenes = pd.read_fwf(path_tableC1_Nagel23, names=colnames, widths=widths, sep='\s+', index_col=0)

df_carmenes["DE-"] = df_carmenes["DE-"].map({"+": 1, "-": -1})
df_carmenes["RAdeg"] = 360/24              *(df_carmenes["RAh"] + df_carmenes["RAm"]/60 + df_carmenes["RAs"]/60**2)
df_carmenes["DECdeg"] = df_carmenes["DE-"] * (df_carmenes["DEd"] + df_carmenes["DEm"]/60 + df_carmenes["DEs"]/60**2)

from astropy.coordinates import SkyCoord
from astropy import units as u
import pandas as pd

radius_conesearch = 2*u.arcmin #30*u.arcmin #1*u.arcsec
criteria_jmagdiff = 1 #10

# Convert RA and Dec from both dataframes into SkyCoord objects
coords_carmenes = SkyCoord(ra=df_carmenes["RAdeg"].values*u.degree, 
                           dec=df_carmenes["DECdeg"].values*u.degree)
coords_single = SkyCoord(ra=df_single["gaia_ra"].values*u.degree, 
                         dec=df_single["gaia_dec"].values*u.degree)

# Perform the cross-match with 1 arcsec search radius
idx_single, idx_carmenes, d2d, _ = coords_carmenes.search_around_sky(coords_single, radius_conesearch)

# Initialize a list to hold indices of rows to drop based on Jmag difference
indices_to_drop = []

for i, (index_car, index_sin) in enumerate(zip(idx_carmenes, idx_single)):
    jmag_diff = abs(df_carmenes.iloc[index_car]["Jmag"] - df_single.iloc[index_sin]["j_mag"])
    jmag_mean = (df_carmenes.iloc[index_car]["Jmag"] + df_single.iloc[index_sin]["j_mag"]) / 2
    percentage_diff = (jmag_diff / jmag_mean) * 100
    
    # Check if the difference is more than 10%
    if percentage_diff > criteria_jmagdiff:
        warning_msg = f"Warning: Target {df_carmenes.iloc[index_car]['Name']} excluded due to Jmag difference" # > 10%
        print(warning_msg)
        indices_to_drop.append(i)

# Remove the matches with Jmag difference > 10%
filtered_idx_carmenes = [i for j, i in enumerate(idx_carmenes) if j not in indices_to_drop]
filtered_idx_single = [i for j, i in enumerate(idx_single) if j not in indices_to_drop]

# Create the final matched DataFrame
matched_df_sin = pd.DataFrame({
    "Name": df_carmenes.iloc[filtered_idx_carmenes]["Name"].values,
    "RAdeg": df_carmenes.iloc[filtered_idx_carmenes]["RAdeg"].values,
    "DECdeg": df_carmenes.iloc[filtered_idx_carmenes]["DECdeg"].values,
    "Jmag_carmenes": df_carmenes.iloc[filtered_idx_carmenes]["Jmag"].values,
    "gaia_ra": df_single.iloc[filtered_idx_single]["gaia_ra"].values,
    "gaia_dec": df_single.iloc[filtered_idx_single]["gaia_dec"].values,
    "j_mag_Sami": df_single.iloc[filtered_idx_single]["j_mag"].values
})

print("To be confident that i > 80:")
required_precision_vsini = (1 - np.sin(80 * np.pi/180)) / 1 * 100
print(required_precision_vsini, "% precision is required for sin(i).")

print("To be confident that i > 70:")
required_precision_vsini = (1 - np.sin(70 * np.pi/180)) / 1 * 100
print(required_precision_vsini, "% precision is required for sin(i).")
print()

print("""Here are some typical precisions for R and P:
    For stellar radius, for example, Ghachoui_2023 (https://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/pdf/2023/09/aa47040-23.pdf) reports 0.0064/0.21*100=3.05% accuracy.
    For period, for example, Irwin_2011 (Note of Table 1) (https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/0004-637X/727/1/56/pdf) reports < 2% accuracy.
    """)

print("""(Added on 240903) I checked the actual precision using Sami's data "poet_targets_06_10_2024_with_periods_Sami240611.numbers".
    For the 30 objects with values in the columns Period, Period_up_err, Period_down_err,
    the precision ranges from 0.188% to 17.7%.
    - The median is 2.539%
    - The average is 6.844%
    - The 68th percentile (the 20th object from the smallest) is at 2.539%
    So, about 2.5% seems reasonable?""")

1.519224698779198 % precision is required for sin(i).

Here are some typical precisions for R and P:
    For stellar radius, for example, Ghachoui_2023 (https://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/pdf/2023/09/aa47040-23.pdf) reports 0.0064/0.21*100=3.05% accuracy.
    For period, for example, Irwin_2011 (Note of Table 1) (https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/0004-637X/727/1/56/pdf) reports < 2% accuracy.
    
(Added on 240903) I checked the actual precision using Sami's data "poet_targets_06_10_2024_with_periods_Sami240611.numbers".
    For the 30 objects with values in the columns Period, Period_up_err, Period_down_err,
    the precision ranges from 0.188% to 17.7%.
    - The median is 2.539%
    - The average is 6.844%
    - The 68th percentile (the 20th object from the smallest) is at 2.539%
    So, about 2.5% seems reasonable?

# Cross-match the objects in UCS with our sample

from astropy.coordinates import SkyCoord
from astropy import units as u
import pandas as pd

radius_conesearch = 5*u.arcmin #30*u.arcmin
criteria_jmagdiff = 1 #10

df_1 = df_single_ANY_ap
df_2 = df_UCS_single_14_M6later #df_UCS_single_14_LT

# Convert RA and Dec from both dataframes into SkyCoord objects
coords_sample2 = SkyCoord(ra=df_2["ra_j2000_formula"].values*u.degree, 
                           dec=df_2["dec_j2000_formula"].values*u.degree)
coords_sample1 = SkyCoord(ra=df_1["gaia_ra"].values*u.degree, 
                         dec=df_1["gaia_dec"].values*u.degree)

# Perform the cross-match with 1 arcsec search radius
idx_1, idx_2, d2d, _ = coords_sample2.search_around_sky(coords_sample1, radius_conesearch)

# Initialize a list to hold indices of rows to drop based on Jmag difference
indices_to_drop = []

for i, (index_car, index_sin) in enumerate(zip(idx_2, idx_1)):
    jmag_diff = abs(df_2.iloc[index_car]["J_2MASS"] - df_1.iloc[index_sin]["j_mag"])
    jmag_mean = (df_2.iloc[index_car]["J_2MASS"] + df_1.iloc[index_sin]["j_mag"]) / 2
    percentage_diff = (jmag_diff / jmag_mean) * 100

    # Check if the difference is more than 10%
    if percentage_diff > criteria_jmagdiff:
        warning_msg = f"Warning: Target {df_2.iloc[index_car]['name']} excluded due to Jmag difference of {percentage_diff:>5.2f} %" # > 10%
        print(warning_msg)
        #print(df_1.iloc[index_sin])
        #print(df_2.iloc[index_car])
        #print(df_1.iloc[index_sin]["j_mag"], df_2.iloc[index_car]["J_2MASS"],)
        #print(df_2.iloc[index_car]["sep_companion"],)
        indices_to_drop.append(i)

    elif df_2.iloc[index_car]["sourceID_Gaia_DR3"] != df_1.iloc[index_sin]["gaia_source_id"]:
        warning_msg = f"Warning: Gaia source ID of {df_2.iloc[index_car]['name']} is {df_2.iloc[index_car]['sourceID_Gaia_DR3']} that is mismatched to our sample, so was excluded." # > 10%
        #print(warning_msg)
        indices_to_drop.append(i)

# Remove the matches with Jmag difference > 10%
filtered_idx_2 = [i for j, i in enumerate(idx_2) if j not in indices_to_drop]
filtered_idx_1 = [i for j, i in enumerate(idx_1) if j not in indices_to_drop]
print(len(filtered_idx_1) == len(filtered_idx_2))

# Create the final matched DataFrame
matched_df = pd.DataFrame({
    "Name": df_2.iloc[filtered_idx_2]["name_simbadable"].values,

# Reyle_2018

def M_G(SpT):
    return -0.020*SpT**2 + 0.985*SpT*1 + 8.298 #M7T6
def GminusGRP(SpT):
    return 0.029*SpT + 1.358 #M7T6
def GminusJ(SpT):
    return 0.108*SpT + 3.603 #M9T6

def estimate_SpType_Reyle18criteria(absGmag):    
    #list_sptype = ["M6", "M7", "M8", "M9", "L0"]
    #arr_M_G_mean = np.array([M_G(6), M_G(7), M_G(8), M_G(9), M_G(10)])
    i_sptype = np.argmin(abs(absGmag - arr_M_G_mean))
    return list_sptype[i_sptype]
